<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870810-0117 </DOCNO><HL> Notable andamp; Quotable</HL><DD> 08/10/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><TEXT>   Beryl Sprinkel, chairman of the Council of Economic Advisers and formerly the top Treasury official for monetary policy, in a March 26 lecture:    The problems that remain in the U.S. economy are not primarily problems that can be addressed with monetary policy -- beyond its normal role in gradually moving toward the goal of long-run price stability, while avoiding being a source of macroeconomic disturbance. In particular, the critical and related problems of the large federal deficit and of the large U.S. trade deficit cannot be resolved by monetary policy. </TEXT></DOC>